WEBVTT

02:21.558 --> 02:23.309
Good morning.

02:55.676 --> 02:57.885
Who puts
the flowers out there?

02:57.970 --> 03:00.721
Can't say for sure. Why?

03:00.806 --> 03:03.057
Could be the sign
of a guilty conscience.

03:03.141 --> 03:06.394
Out here,
we just call it "Being nice."

03:06.478 --> 03:08.938
Or maybe,
whoever's doing it is superstitious.

03:09.106 --> 03:11.732
Yeah? How so?

03:11.817 --> 03:15.069
Well, they figure
if they honor the dead,

03:15.153 --> 03:19.448
maybe their kids
won't end up like them two girls did.

03:19.533 --> 03:21.033
That's just magical thinking.

03:22.494 --> 03:24.412
You ever been out to the creek,

03:24.580 --> 03:26.455
where Ann Nash's body
was found, Detective?

03:26.540 --> 03:27.748
Yeah.

03:27.833 --> 03:32.169
Well, it's just smooth water
rolling over sand, now.

03:32.254 --> 03:34.255
Well, after Ann died,

03:34.339 --> 03:36.757
the townsfolk went out there
and pulled the rocks out.

03:38.343 --> 03:40.261
The same ones
that snagged the clothesline

03:40.345 --> 03:41.637
that was around Ann's neck.

03:41.722 --> 03:43.514
They loaded them into a pickup truck,

03:43.682 --> 03:46.434
took them out to the edge of town,
and smashed 'em.

03:46.560 --> 03:48.769
Nice and smooth.

03:48.896 --> 03:54.025
Like they figured that destroying them
would ward off any future evil.

03:55.819 --> 03:58.070
Well, I guess
they left a rock, or two.

04:27.142 --> 04:29.810
How does it fit?

04:29.895 --> 04:33.189
I have a navy,
I mean, if you'd rather.

04:33.273 --> 04:36.025
No, I just think my hips
are a little higher than yours.

04:36.109 --> 04:37.193
Curvy.

04:38.987 --> 04:41.572
It's fine. I'm fine, fine.

04:48.872 --> 04:51.082
Let me do that.

04:59.341 --> 05:02.843
This funeral is going to be very hard.

05:03.470 --> 05:05.429
I loved those girls.

05:05.514 --> 05:07.056
How did you know those girls, again?

05:07.432 --> 05:12.186
Camille, I'm very involved in
the community. It's our family's duty.

05:17.442 --> 05:22.071
More dead little girls.
As if Marian wasn't enough.

05:22.239 --> 05:23.614
Were you friends with Natalie?

05:23.699 --> 05:26.867
Enough to be sad, too,
which is why I should go.

05:26.994 --> 05:29.453
You're gonna stay here with Gayla,
and have ice cream.

05:29.579 --> 05:32.581
I want to know where you are.

05:32.708 --> 05:34.458
Camille, maybe,
you should stay back, too,

05:34.960 --> 05:38.796
-given your state of mind.
-I have to go. It's my job.

05:38.922 --> 05:43.467
I think Camille knows how to behave.
Adora, we don't want to be late.

05:43.552 --> 05:48.639
We're fine. And I don't want you
to talk like that, like it's work.

05:48.807 --> 05:51.225
We're going to the funeral
to support that poor family.

05:51.643 --> 05:55.229
Ladies, can we please go?

05:55.313 --> 05:56.605
Yes.

06:01.403 --> 06:03.654
I love you, love you, love you.

06:03.739 --> 06:05.990
- Are you gonna ride with us?
- No, no. I'm gonna drive.

06:06.074 --> 06:07.491
I have to grab my purse.

06:08.910 --> 06:11.579
- I'll wait in the car.
- All right.

06:13.999 --> 06:16.667
Morning.

06:16.877 --> 06:18.002
Kansas City.

06:18.086 --> 06:20.004
You know, I've been thinking.

06:21.798 --> 06:24.967
Why does a killer
change his MO like that?

06:25.052 --> 06:29.430
The first body left at the kill site
in the forest, but Natalie,

06:29.514 --> 06:33.809
she's dumped in the middle of town
like a prop, or a doll.

06:33.935 --> 06:35.352
My daughter had one of them dolls.

06:36.104 --> 06:38.981
Little "O" for a mouth.
Creepy little fucking things.

06:39.066 --> 06:43.069
Getting her there was risky.
Way more chance of getting caught.

06:43.195 --> 06:45.905
Well, some killers want to get caught.
A cry for help.

06:46.364 --> 06:48.491
This one likes making
people scared for their girls.

06:48.575 --> 06:51.494
Can we just save The Silence
of the Lambs routine for another time?

06:52.120 --> 06:56.040
Look, Bill, I get it, okay.
This is your home.

06:56.124 --> 06:57.666
You gotta look out for your people,

06:57.751 --> 07:00.002
but odds are
the killer is gonna show up here.

07:00.087 --> 07:01.295
Soak up the atmosphere.

07:01.421 --> 07:03.297
I read them books, too,
Agent Starling.

07:03.423 --> 07:05.758
Watch out for anyone trying to
insert himself into the action.

07:05.842 --> 07:07.259
Anyone trying too hard
with the family.

07:07.344 --> 07:09.386
The nature of this crime,
it's personal.

07:09.471 --> 07:11.055
This guy wants to rule the town.

07:11.139 --> 07:15.518
Well, he may not rule it,
but he sure as hell got our attention.

07:19.356 --> 07:21.148
-Look good?
-That's fine.

07:21.233 --> 07:23.317
Yeah, I know you're fond of me,

07:23.401 --> 07:25.486
but don't think
this means we're married.

07:33.745 --> 07:38.582
Come on in, Mrs. Crellin.
This way, please. Sorry, folks.

07:47.050 --> 07:48.509
I'm so sorry.

07:56.518 --> 08:01.272
Come on, Sweetie. I saved you a place.
Get your cute, little butt in here.

08:02.774 --> 08:07.820
Good Lord. I don't think
I've seen you in a month of Sundays.

08:07.946 --> 08:11.240
-You saw me at the search, Jackie.
-I didn't really see you.

08:11.867 --> 08:14.034
See, it was that sweet tea,
and its kick.

08:15.537 --> 08:17.246
Please tell me y'all
aren't waiting on us.

08:17.372 --> 08:19.915
Well, we weren't waiting
for the pastor. That's for sure.

08:21.042 --> 08:22.668
You look great.

08:22.752 --> 08:24.253
I don't know what I expected.

08:24.337 --> 08:28.424
-You look absolutely...
-Jackie, inside voice. It's a funeral.

08:30.051 --> 08:31.343
You look great.

08:41.229 --> 08:45.441
They can't release the body
because of the investigation.

08:45.525 --> 08:49.278
Can you even imagine?

08:59.080 --> 09:02.666
That's Natalie's mama and daddy.
They're divorced.

09:03.460 --> 09:05.878
They keep to themselves.

09:14.095 --> 09:17.765
We gather here, to celebrate

09:17.849 --> 09:19.350
the life of Natalie Keene.

09:20.060 --> 09:23.437
Her death is a great tragedy,

09:23.563 --> 09:27.733
but we must
turn our hearts to the light.

09:27.817 --> 09:32.196
We begin with some words of comfort
from Natalie's mother, Jeannie Keene.

09:32.906 --> 09:33.948
Jeannie?

09:42.999 --> 09:46.293
Natalie was a surprise baby,

09:46.419 --> 09:49.338
but we were grateful for her.

09:49.422 --> 09:54.677
Almost six years
after our sweet son, a girl.

09:56.263 --> 09:59.932
I taped a pink ribbon
to her little, bald head.

10:00.016 --> 10:01.141
She snatched it off.

10:01.309 --> 10:04.103
Six weeks old,
and our girl knew what she wanted.

10:05.355 --> 10:07.064
She was always like that.

10:07.148 --> 10:12.820
A spitfire, a contrarian,
a tomboy, a goofball.

10:12.904 --> 10:15.948
Smart as a whip,
she didn't suffer fools.

10:16.700 --> 10:20.411
I remember when she was two,
I was making goo-goo eyes at her.

10:20.495 --> 10:23.539
I swear she rolled her eyes.

10:23.665 --> 10:28.585
In our first home in Philadelphia,
she'd sneak out and explore the city.

10:28.795 --> 10:30.796
In Wind Gap, she roamed the woods,

10:30.880 --> 10:34.925
and would report back to us
on everything she saw.

10:35.093 --> 10:37.219
She talked a lot...

10:41.182 --> 10:45.686
She talked a lot
when she had something to say.

10:45.770 --> 10:48.772
And was quiet if she didn't.

10:49.107 --> 10:52.735
I wish more grown-ups had that gift.

10:53.320 --> 10:55.404
It is horrible to lose a child.

10:56.323 --> 10:59.199
It is unbearable to lose her this way,

10:59.826 --> 11:02.202
to a murdering fiend.

11:03.288 --> 11:08.208
I know I'm supposed to be forgiving,
but I am furious.

11:08.376 --> 11:10.127
I know what good people say.

11:10.420 --> 11:14.965
"An eye for an eye
makes the whole world blind."

11:15.091 --> 11:17.092
I wish I could be that gentle.

11:18.136 --> 11:20.512
I want revenge.

11:20.597 --> 11:24.475
I want justice

11:24.601 --> 11:26.977
for her daddy,

11:27.062 --> 11:30.939
who will never get to walk her
down the aisle.

11:31.024 --> 11:34.360
For her brother,
who was her best friend.

11:35.987 --> 11:37.821
And for me,

11:37.947 --> 11:41.575
who will never, ever

11:41.701 --> 11:43.494
recover from her loss.

11:43.620 --> 11:46.497
We love you, Natalie.

12:45.890 --> 12:49.143
Heaven does, indeed,
have another angel,

12:49.310 --> 12:53.897
but we must know that Natalie has gone
to a better place, to sit with God.

12:54.023 --> 12:56.692
Camille, please.
For the sake of the family, please.

12:56.776 --> 12:59.445
Now, would you please stand
as we say, together, the words

12:59.529 --> 13:00.863
Our Savior Christ has taught us?

13:03.783 --> 13:06.243
Our Father, Who art in heaven,

13:06.995 --> 13:08.704
hallowed be Thy name,

13:08.955 --> 13:11.748
Thy kingdom come, Thy will be done,

13:12.000 --> 13:14.501
on Earth as it is in heaven.

13:14.627 --> 13:17.629
Give us this day our daily bread,

13:17.797 --> 13:19.965
and forgive us our trespasses,

13:20.091 --> 13:23.385
as we forgive those
who trespass against us.

13:23.595 --> 13:25.929
And lead us not into temptation,

13:26.055 --> 13:27.723
but deliver us from evil.

13:51.581 --> 13:53.332
-Hi, Sammie.
-Hi.

14:17.357 --> 14:20.943
-Hey, sis.
-What are you doing here?

14:21.069 --> 14:24.655
Shouldn't you be home,
eating ice cream?

14:24.781 --> 14:28.116
Any chance I can
bum a few bucks for the Sprite?

14:28.201 --> 14:29.660
-Sprite?
-Yeah.

14:29.786 --> 14:31.245
Sure.

14:34.123 --> 14:36.625
I knew you'd be cool.

14:36.751 --> 14:39.127
You all, isn't my sister the coolest?

14:39.295 --> 14:40.629
-So cool.
-So cool.

14:40.713 --> 14:42.089
So cool.

14:42.173 --> 14:43.590
Don't try to work me, Amma.

14:43.675 --> 14:45.759
I've been playing
that game for 20 years.

14:45.843 --> 14:46.969
- Twenty years?
- Yeah.

14:47.220 --> 14:49.346
Then you're old enough to be my mom.

14:49.514 --> 14:52.182
-Do you know my mom?
-Shut up, Jodes.

14:52.350 --> 14:55.519
Amma, Mama wants you home,
and I want you home.

14:56.729 --> 14:59.189
It's dangerous out there for you.
People are killing little girls.

14:59.732 --> 15:01.775
Not the cool ones.

15:02.443 --> 15:04.403
Yeah, we're going
straight to Kelsey's,

15:04.487 --> 15:05.654
and I'll be home before curfew.

15:06.114 --> 15:07.322
I swear.

15:07.407 --> 15:08.991
Straight there?

15:09.075 --> 15:10.409
And you call me if you need a ride?

15:10.827 --> 15:12.327
-You promise?
-Yeah, I promise.

15:12.662 --> 15:13.745
Thank you.

15:13.830 --> 15:15.122
Make sure you get home before...

15:15.206 --> 15:18.125
-Mama?
-Yeah. Okay.

15:18.209 --> 15:20.210
Amma. Careful with the vodka.

15:20.378 --> 15:21.461
Yeah.

15:22.755 --> 15:24.172
-Thank you, girls.
-Thank you, Sammie.

15:24.257 --> 15:26.550
- Bye, girls.
- Bye!

15:26.968 --> 15:30.220
Jeannie Keene is having
all the mourners over to her house.

15:30.305 --> 15:31.597
I think that's pretty nice.

15:31.764 --> 15:34.266
When Marian died,
Mama shuttered our house

15:34.392 --> 15:35.892
for a year with us inside.

15:37.520 --> 15:40.230
Listen. I know this is
delicate ground for you.

15:40.982 --> 15:42.941
-It's not.
-Okay, well, good.

15:43.026 --> 15:45.611
Then get as many personal details
as you can,

15:45.695 --> 15:47.613
and, remember, you're not there

15:47.697 --> 15:49.197
-to solve the mystery.
-Yeah.

15:49.282 --> 15:50.616
Well, the brother interests me.

15:50.908 --> 15:55.662
He's not your typical Wind Gap fare.

15:55.788 --> 15:59.833
Excellent. We want characters.
Tell us about the Keene house.

15:59.917 --> 16:04.755
Are Natalie's shoes still out?
Are the photos friendly, or familiar?

16:04.839 --> 16:06.423
Piano, books?

16:06.507 --> 16:08.383
Are the paintings
on the wall original,

16:08.468 --> 16:11.303
or from Antiques 'R' Us, like ours?

16:11.387 --> 16:14.473
Well, why don't I go
through the ice box while I'm at it?

16:14.557 --> 16:16.642
Hey, don't be a wise-ass, kiddo.
You know what I mean.

16:16.726 --> 16:18.977
This could be your big break
if you do it right.

16:19.062 --> 16:21.813
-You gotta stop saying that.
-All right.

16:22.023 --> 16:25.067
Don't go gentle.
Get what you need for this story.

16:25.151 --> 16:28.612
-You're right. Yes, sir.
-Okay, kiddo.

16:28.696 --> 16:31.031
-Bye-bye.
-Bye.

16:39.540 --> 16:41.625
-If you're about to say...
-"You can't solve all the problems

16:41.709 --> 16:43.043
-"of the entire world?"
-The other one.

16:43.127 --> 16:45.420
-"Hope you know what you're doing?"
-Bingo.

16:45.505 --> 16:49.549
I understand what you're trying to do,
but what she needs now, is time.

16:49.634 --> 16:51.218
Don't we all?

16:52.470 --> 16:54.846
Look, she's a great investigator,
could be a great writer,

16:54.931 --> 16:59.101
maybe even have a life,
but she needs to deal with her issues.

16:59.268 --> 17:01.937
And stop thinking
that vodka doesn't stay on her breath.

17:02.063 --> 17:04.439
You can't fix her
like another thing in this house.

17:05.316 --> 17:09.611
Not now. Can't take that on, too.

17:09.696 --> 17:10.737
I'll think about it.

17:12.365 --> 17:14.157
-No, I will.
-Yeah, right.

17:24.585 --> 17:26.211
Yeah, right!

18:54.175 --> 18:55.675
I don't care
who told you to come!

18:55.760 --> 18:56.968
Get the fuck out of this house!

18:57.053 --> 18:59.888
Get out of this house! Come on!
Don't make me tell you again!

19:00.139 --> 19:01.556
Just beat it! Get out of here!

19:01.641 --> 19:03.308
- Fuck you!
- Mr. Keene, come on, now.

19:03.392 --> 19:04.476
Beat it!

19:04.560 --> 19:06.603
Shut it!

19:06.687 --> 19:09.064
Son of a bitch!

19:39.679 --> 19:41.680
She thought
that was a good idea, too.

19:41.764 --> 19:42.806
I agree.

19:52.817 --> 19:54.860
Well, well, well.
Camille's here.

19:58.781 --> 20:00.615
I'm not sure that's so.

20:00.700 --> 20:04.995
Adora says it's a comfort
having Marian's room.

20:11.002 --> 20:16.047
The little bitch
just waltzed right in here.

20:23.764 --> 20:24.931
No, patrol is what we do.

20:25.016 --> 20:27.601
No, I say, we start over
on the beaner side of town.

20:27.685 --> 20:29.019
Think about it.
A man who could slaughter

20:29.103 --> 20:30.854
pigs all day, that's the type of man

20:30.938 --> 20:32.439
that can yank out
a little girl's teeth.

20:32.523 --> 20:35.025
- All that blood.
- Okay, Chris, stop.

20:35.109 --> 20:36.318
You know where you're going?

20:36.402 --> 20:38.987
Stumbling back to your bed is where.

20:39.155 --> 20:40.572
I brought John some food.

20:41.449 --> 20:42.574
You need to eat, John.

20:42.658 --> 20:45.911
Ashley, John will eat
when he wants to eat. Thank you.

20:46.329 --> 20:47.913
Okay.

20:53.002 --> 20:54.252
Would you look at them?

20:54.337 --> 20:56.922
Just sitting all by themselves
in a group of people.

20:57.089 --> 21:00.008
And then they wonder why
they're not a part of this town.

21:00.217 --> 21:02.886
The funeral was nice, at least.

21:02.970 --> 21:05.931
Well, that girl
she described is not Natalie.

21:06.015 --> 21:07.390
Believe me. I should know.

21:14.857 --> 21:16.399
Appreciate it.

21:34.251 --> 21:35.710
Deputy Coroner's office.

21:40.841 --> 21:44.177
Camille! I heard
you were back in town.

21:44.261 --> 21:46.137
Watch the liquor, watch the men.

21:46.222 --> 21:47.931
I'm kidding.

21:48.766 --> 21:50.392
How are you?
You never come home.

21:50.476 --> 21:52.644
Well, she's in big-shit St. Louis.

21:52.770 --> 21:53.853
I love St. Louis.

21:53.938 --> 21:55.814
Dan and I took the girls there
after Christmas last year.

21:55.898 --> 21:59.484
Jack and I were thinking about that.
Taking the kids for a visit.

21:59.568 --> 22:00.902
I have four, all boys.

22:01.862 --> 22:04.280
- Do you have kids, Camille?
- Here.

22:04.448 --> 22:06.866
-I said I'm not hungry.
-Fine.

22:06.951 --> 22:09.744
- Fuck it.
- Sorry.

22:09.912 --> 22:11.496
I guess I have five boys.

22:11.664 --> 22:14.207
What about you, Camille?
You must have a boyfriend.

22:14.792 --> 22:16.126
Do you guys know the Keene family?

22:16.210 --> 22:18.795
You know, Angie's due
in September. Look at this.

22:18.921 --> 22:21.506
-Congratulations.
-I know I look big.

22:21.590 --> 22:23.758
I get bigger every time.
What can you do?

22:23.843 --> 22:25.468
So, the brother, John,

22:25.553 --> 22:27.429
he seems to be taking
the death kind of...

22:27.513 --> 22:29.222
He's been crying up a storm.

22:29.348 --> 22:32.058
-I don't mean to be mean...
-Sure, you do.

22:33.102 --> 22:34.811
But it's a bit much.

22:34.895 --> 22:37.522
It's like he's a little boy.
A lot of tears.

22:37.648 --> 22:39.065
Well, did he fit in at school?

22:39.150 --> 22:41.901
Little Ashley Wheeler made sure
he fit in with the right crowd.

22:42.028 --> 22:45.447
She's a cheerleader.
Like us in the day, right?

22:45.531 --> 22:47.907
- Yeah.
- Until you quit us.

22:48.200 --> 22:50.368
But he is an odd damn duck.

22:50.786 --> 22:53.705
He seems sorta gay to me.

22:53.789 --> 22:56.624
I mean, that would make sense.
If he's the one who did it.

22:56.709 --> 22:59.836
Because sometimes, when siblings
have unnatural affections,

22:59.920 --> 23:01.713
that leads to other things.

23:01.839 --> 23:03.673
God, you watch too much news.

23:03.758 --> 23:04.799
Camille Preaker!

23:04.884 --> 23:06.342
So damn sick
of your damn theories.

23:06.427 --> 23:07.886
You owe me a scoop...

23:07.970 --> 23:11.347
-It was nice catching up.
-...reporter girl.

23:12.224 --> 23:13.349
I hate her dress.

23:13.476 --> 23:14.934
Thank you.

23:16.353 --> 23:20.190
What are you doing
with those nasty vipers? Lord!

23:21.776 --> 23:24.569
I'm so happy to see you.

23:24.653 --> 23:26.905
I mean, your mother shows me
pictures of you, but...

23:27.073 --> 23:29.324
She does? What pictures?

23:29.408 --> 23:33.787
Well, she paints a picture of you.

23:34.121 --> 23:36.706
-She's so proud.
-I do not believe you, Jackie.

23:36.791 --> 23:38.875
Well, that's 'cause I lie like a rug.

23:39.335 --> 23:41.711
You turned out so...

23:41.921 --> 23:44.547
Wonderful, smart, beautiful,

23:44.715 --> 23:48.176
successful, and brave.

23:48.260 --> 23:51.888
-You do lie, Jackie.
-No, I mean it.

23:51.972 --> 23:54.682
I mean it. You tackled those demons.

23:54.767 --> 23:58.311
My demons are not remotely tackled.
They're just mildly concussed.

23:58.437 --> 24:02.982
Well, I'd say that's better than
the rest of us, isn't it?

24:03.150 --> 24:06.111
-How's your mama doing?
-She's sad.

24:06.237 --> 24:10.782
I wish you knew her
before Marian. She was lovely,

24:11.534 --> 24:13.743
and frivolous, like a kite.

24:14.537 --> 24:17.205
You still lying, Jackie?

24:17.331 --> 24:19.582
I don't think so.

24:24.421 --> 24:27.132
You're the best.

25:41.540 --> 25:43.541
I didn't want him to starve.

25:46.629 --> 25:50.298
I'm sorry for your loss.

25:50.424 --> 25:53.092
She stunned ants
and fed them to her spiders.

25:53.219 --> 25:55.011
It was nasty,

25:55.095 --> 25:59.224
but it was good for Natalie,
the outdoors.

26:01.936 --> 26:04.145
Well,

26:04.271 --> 26:08.191
sounds like she was a tomboy.

26:08.275 --> 26:10.735
Was she playing outside
when she went missing?

26:10.819 --> 26:14.697
